# Check for numeric outliers
numeric_cols = ['Age', 'Minutes Streamed Per Day', 'Number of Songs Liked', 
                'Discover Weekly Engagement (%)', 'Repeat Song Rate (%)']

print("\nNumeric outliers (values outside 1.5*IQR):")
for col_1 in numeric_cols:
    q1 = df[col_1].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = df[col_1].quantile(0.75)
    iqr = q3 - q1
    lower_bound = q1 - 1.5*iqr
    upper_bound = q3 + 1.5*iqr
    outliers = df[(df[col_1] < lower_bound) | (df[col_1] > upper_bound)]
    print(f"{col_1}: {len(outliers)} outliers")

Numeric outliers (values outside 1.5*IQR):
Age: 0 outliers
Minutes Streamed Per Day: 0 outliers
Number of Songs Liked: 0 outliers
Discover Weekly Engagement (%): 0 outliers
Repeat Song Rate (%): 0 outliers
  • The code detects numerical outliers by applying the Interquartile Range (IQR) method for columns identification.
  • It finds the 25th percentile point Q1 and 75th percentile point Q3 before calculating the IQR value by subtracting Q3 from Q1.
  • Moreover the lower and upper bounds which determine normal values are calculated as Q1 - 1.5 * IQR and Q3 + 1.5 * IQR respectively.
  • The data points which fall beyond the defined upper or lower bounds officially classify as outliers.
  • The program identifies and counts outliers that exist within numerical columns before displaying the results.

# Additional advanced visualisation: Streaming Platform Preferences by Country (Facet Grid)

plt.ylabel('Country', fontsize=12)

plt.show()

The plot utilizes 'Set2' colors to present the countries organized by user numbers in descending order. A proper visualization method helps to display the variations in streaming platform choices across different countries. Summary of Analysis and Findings(415 Words)¶

Key Information About the Data¶

  • The dataset includes 12 columns that contain a total of 5,000 entries and shows a validation check revealing consistency and absence of missing or inconsistent values.

The dataset contains three data types consisting of integers (age and minutes streamed per day), floats (discover weekly engagement and repeat song rate) and objects (country and streaming platform)

According to summary statistics the user base consists of 36.66-year-old participants spending 309.24 minutes daily while liking 253.52 songs on average. The average discover weekly engagement stands at 50.30% and users listen to their favorite songs again at a rate of 42.39%.

Statistically Significant Results¶

  • The correlation investigation among numerical fields (age and minutes streamed per day and number of songs liked and discover weekly engagement and repeat song rate) demonstrated low correlation rates without showing noteworthy linear patterns. The calculated correlation value between age and daily streaming duration measured 0.004 which implied little relationship between these variables.
  • The numerical data contains no outliers or impossible values within its columns. The dataset includes categories such as country and streaming platform which show appropriate and uniform values.

Key Insights from Visualisations¶

  • Age Distribution:The estimated kernel density plot in the histogram shows that users are distributed normally by age and their mean age stands at 36.66 years. Most users among the sample group fall between 25 years old and 49 years old according to the analyzed data visualization.
  • Streaming Platform Popularity:The graphic displayed how users distributed themselves between various streaming platforms. Customer choice favored Amazon Music because it led the rankings while Tidal and Deezer maintained close positions yet Apple Music had the smallest audience.
  • Top Genres: Users primarily listened to music in Reggae, Jazz, EDM but Rock, R&B, Metal were also significant choices. User preference surveys showed Pop genre occupied the bottom position among other listed genres.
  • Subscription Types: User demographics show that premium subscriptions existed among 50.52% of the user base with free account users comprising 49.48% of the total population.
  • Listening Time Preferences: Nighttime usage of music platforms by users reached 34.9% whereas afternoons and mornings displayed 32.68% and 32.42%, respectively.

Conclusion¶

The research study determined three main music streaming patterns namely the average user age at 36.7 and the top platforms as Amazon Music and Tidal alongside the most preferred genres as Reggae and Jazz.Age groups did not show any significant relationship patterns when it comes to music listener behaviors. The frequency split between premium (50%) consumers together with knowledge about peak usage hours at night can help streaming businesses optimize their marketing strategies while improving individual user interactions.
